As Carey wrote to Dr. Math
On 09/21/2004 at 15:13:35 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>I know that we use SSS, ASA, and SAS to prove congruent triangles.  
>Why is there no AAS?  
>
>
>[Difficulty]
>I know why SSA doesn't work, but I am having trouble explaining to my 
>students why AAS doesn't work.  I am trying to come up with an 
>example to disprove it, but I am having a difficult time.
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>I have tried to set up the triangles with two angles the same and one 
>side the same, but that would mean the third sides are congruent and 
>then you can use ASA.  Is that accurate or is there more to it?

You got it -- except you said "third sides are congruent" when you
meant angles.

Since the angles always add up to 180, once you have two angles
you have them all, so ASA, AAS, SAA, AAAS, AASA, ASAA, SAAA
are all the same!

